chieved through electoral systems? How do straight voters view out LGBTQ politicians, and what part do the media play in framing these perceptions? What pathways to power do LGBTQ politicians follow? Do they represent LGBTQ people and communities in particular, and, if so, how is this role articulated? And finally, how do Canadian party ideologies shape LGBTQ representation? The contributors to Queering Representation address these questions by offering diverse, nuanced readings of political representation, shining a spotlight on relations between electoral processes and LGBTQ communities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aElectionszCanada. 0aGay peoplexPolitical activityzCanada. 0aGay politicianszCanada. 0aGaysxPolitical activityzCanada. 0aPolitical campaignszCanada. 0aPolitical candidateszCanada. 0aSexual minoritiesxPolitical activityzCanada. 0aSexual minority politicianszCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / World / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aAtkins, Curtis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoily, Frédéric, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Steven D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeGagne, Alexa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEveritt, Joanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGorman-Murray, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJeffrey, Brooke, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKay, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLalancette, Mireille, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNash, Catherine J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPerrella, Andrea M.L